Data Transformation

  • babynames from the babynames package include all baby names with at least 5 uses.
  • What geoms should be used for this graph?

dplyr package

  • dplyr is a package in the tidyverse for cleaning data
  • We will learn the five key dplyr function that allow you to solve the vast majority of data transformation challenges.
    • filter() - Pick observations by their values
    • arrange() - reorder the rows
    • select() - pick variables by their names
    • mutate() - create new variables with functions of existing variables
    • summarize() - Collapse many values down to a single summary

The functions on the previous slide can all be used in conjunction with group_by()

- Changes the scope of each function from operating on the entire dataset
to operating on it group-by-group  
- These six functions provide the verbs for the language of data 
transformation.

All six functions work similarly:

1) The first argument is the data frame (tibble).  
2) The subsequent arguments describe what to do with the data frame, using
  the variable names (without quotes).  
3) The result is a new data frame.

Together these properties make it easy to chain together multiple simple steps toi achieve a complex result.

select()

How do we extract just the column of baby names and proportions?

select()

How do we extract just the columns of baby names and proportions?

select(babynames, name, prop)

Select helpers

  • : selects a range of columns

      select(babynames, name:prop)

  • - selects every column but

      select(babynames, -c(name,prop))

  • starts_with() selects columns that start with

      select(babynames, starts_with("n"))

More select helpers

  • ends_with() selects columns that end with

      select(babynames,ends_with("e"))

  • contains() selects columns that contain

      select(babynames,contains("e"))

  • num_range() selects columns named in prefix, number style

      select(xxxx,num_range("x",1:5))

$ and `select()

$ extracts column contents as a vector.
select() extracts column contents as a tibble.

select(babynames, n)

Missing values

One important feature of R that can make comparison tricky are missing values

- Denoted as `NA` in R ("Not Available")  
- `NA` represents an unknown value so missing values are "contageous": 
almost any operation involving an unknown will also be unknown.  
  NA > 5
  NA + 10
  NA == NA

  NA | FALSE
  NA & FALSE
  NA*0
  Inf*0

Handling missing values

  • To determine if a value is missing, use is.na().
  • filter() only includes rows where the condition is TRUE; it excludes both FALSE and NA values.
  • If you want to preserve missing values, you will have to ask for the explicitly.
df <- tibble(x = c(1, NA, 3))
filter(df, x > 1)
## # A tibble: 1  1
##       x
##   <dbl>
## 1     3
filter(df, is.na(x) | x > 1)
## # A tibble: 2  1
##       x
##   <dbl>
## 1    NA
## 2     3

Boolean Operators

filter(babynames, name == "Garrett", year == 1880)

filter(babynames, name == "Garrett" & year == 1880)

Common mistakes

Collapsing multiple tests into one

filter(babynames, 10 < n < 20)
filter(babynames, 10 < n, n < 20)

Stringing together many tests (when you could use %in%)

filter(babynames, n == 5 | n == 6 | n == 7 | n == 8)
filter(babynames, n %in% c(5, 6, 7, 8))
